<br>
We disallow all advertising here, although regulars can post links to their own web sites and any other sites that are worth a look, provided it is not seeing as blatant spam.<br>
<br>
We used to move all spam posts to the staff forum without comment.  Now we edit out the link, but leave the post intact.<br>
<br>
The benefit of disallowing advertising gives us the power to remove spam from the main forums without forum, thereby keeping the forums clean.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  Problems with the current situation</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
- We could be cutting off a lot of potential members by disallowing ALL advertising.<br>
- We could be missing out on potential candidates to join the network as an affiliate.<br>
- Editing someone's very first post may not give a good impression.  Do we edit everything?  How do they know either way?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  Proposed changes</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
To bring in some new members who are genuinely interested in creative arts and wish to share their site with us, we could create a dedicated advertising forum.  It would not be openly described as an &quot;advertising&quot; forum, but a place for people to show off their creative skills.  That could also interest some people who simply want comments on the design of their web site, which I also think is fine.  &quot;Visit my board!&quot; or &quot;Visit my web site!&quot; is NOT fine, though.<br>
<br>
I think that if we have a dedicated links forum - but only for sites that are related to creativity and are therefore relevant to the bbarden network - we may be onto a winner.<br>
<br>
Not everyone who posts a link is a spammer. I think we could learn a very valuable lesson from this.<br>
<br>
Your comments are very valuable to help us make the right decision.  Please share your thoughts and suggestions here. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.bbarden.com/img/em/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
